    What's the difference between a hair pin and a bobby pin?
    An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
    AI Overview
    Hair pins and bobby pins are both used for securing hair, but they have different designs and uses. Bobby pins are closed, double-pronged pins that grip hair with pressure, while hair pins are U-shaped, open pins that offer a lighter hold, often used for updos. 
    This video explains the difference between bobby pins and hair pins:
    1m
    DIY Hairschool
    YouTube Oct 14, 2024
    Here's a more detailed breakdown:
    Bobby Pins:
    • Design: Closed, double-pronged pins that create tension to hold hair. 
    • Use: Primarily used to secure hair against the scalp, taming flyaways, and holding sections of hair in place. 
    • Hold: Offers a stronger hold due to the pressure and tension created by the two prongs. 
    Hair Pins:
    • Design: U-shaped pins, often with ridges or curves for better grip.
    • Use: Commonly used for creating and securing buns, updos, and other styles where a more gentle hold is needed.
    • Hold: Provides a lighter hold compared to bobby pins, allowing for more natural movement.

      Why do they call them bobby pins?
      An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
      AI Overview
      Bobby pins are named for the bob hairstyle that became popular in the 1920s; the pins were created to help women hold their short, cropped "bobbed" hair in place, functioning as a necessary tool for the modern, liberated styles of the time. The name refers to the hairstyle, not a person named Bobby. 
      The Origin of the "Bob" Hairstyle 
      • Cultural shift:
        In the early 20th century, the bob hairstylea short, sleek cutgained significant popularity, challenging traditional long hairstyles.
      • Empowering styles:
        The bob was seen as a symbol of women's growing independence and a move towards more modern and liberated styles during the Jazz Age.
      The Invention and Purpose of the Bobby Pin 
      • A practical solution:
        The new bob hairstyle required a simple way to keep hair in place, and the bobby pin was invented to meet this need. 
      • A game-changer:
        The bobby pin was smaller, stronger, and easier to conceal than older hair tools, giving women more control over their look. 
      • The connection:
        The pin was specifically designed to secure and maintain the look of the bob, leading to its name, "bobby pin". 
      In Summary
      The bobby pin got its name because it was a key accessory for the fashionable "bobbed" hair of the 1920s, a trend that helped define women's fashion and liberation during that era.

        Salon Care Professional Supreme Bobby Pins hold hair and hairpieces in place. They can be used to secure hair styles like French Twist or Chignon. To use, slide into hair with the prongs open and then close over the hair to hold it in place.

        Are bobby pins good for your hair?
        People commonly say that bobby pins hurt their scalps, which is a symptom of too-tight styles (avoid those no matter what you're using!), but I would also add that bobby pins aren't meant to be used right on your scalp. They're for tucking in and securing small sections, not holding up a high updo.Mar 7, 2023
